 through a Critical Design Review (CDR), qualification, integration with the GMD Weapon System, ground and flight testing, and AUR production. MDA established future
 KPs and ground and flight tests to evaluate Next Generation Interceptor and GMD Weapon System performance supporting future production decisions. A contract
 option is available to extend efforts through December 2028 for activities and hardware to support Missile Defense System Ground Testing, as well as activities and
 hardware to deliver up to ten (10) Next Generation Interceptor units in an integrated AUR configuration to support the corresponding Missile Defense System Flight
 Test campaigns. Contemporaneous with KP #1, the two Next Generation Interceptor contractors submitted not-to-exceed cost estimates for an additional test article
 and 20 production units, broken into two production lots. The Next Generation Interceptor contractor is required to deliver a firm production proposal at CDR. The Next
 Generation Interceptor competitive acquisition strategy met its intended goals for the technology development phase to reduce technical risk, encourage schedule
 acceleration, and support the Department's ability to field a system capable of negating the expanding threat.

 The GWS Contract was competitively awarded to Northrop Grumman Systems Corporation in July 2022 to design, develop, produce, and test the upgrades to the
 GMD Weapon System. In addition, the GWS Contract included the sustainment planning, and maintenance of the currently fielded GMD Weapon System. The
 GWS contractor is responsible for developing weapon system solutions, including fire control and communication systems improvements, required to update the
 legacy system to remain effective while the Next Generation Interceptor is under development, as well as, preparing for the seamless introduction of Next Generation
 Interceptor and other future Missile Defense System capabilities. The GWS contractor will incorporate the interface updates adding the Next Generation Interceptors
 to the fleet, provide United States Northern Command the capability to operate the GMD Weapon System with a mixed fleet of Ground Based Interceptors and Next
 Generation Interceptors, and identify and develop solutions for message exchanges between the GMD Weapon System and in-flight payloads, all while maintaining a
 robust cyber defense network capable of detecting and defending against current and future cybersecurity threats.

 The GMD SITR Contract was competitively awarded to The Boeing Company on September 1, 2022 to support the MDA as the GMD Weapon System Integrator by
 providing a synergistic approach in executing the GMD engineering, integration, test, and readiness of the integrated GMD Weapon System. The SITR contractor
 is the Government's partner for day-to-day operation and sustainment of the GMD Weapon System alongside USNORTHCOM. While the Government maintains
 overall weapon system integration responsibilities and authority, the SITR contractor assumes a supporting role aiding with GMD Weapon System integration, GMD
 contributions to Missile Defense System enterprise level integration, and GMD requirements verification.

 GMD also uses MDA Consolidated Support contracts for engineering and technical support; studies, analyses, and evaluations; and management and professional
 services to GMD functional organizations and project offices. With a focus to achieve Small Business goals, MDA is leveraging existing MDA Consolidated Support
 contracts and will utilize MDA competitively awarded new contracts to acquire Fiscal Years 2020-2030 Advisory and Assistance Services support.

 Other Enabling GMD Acquisition Strategies (budgeted for in Program Element 0603882C).

 The GMD Boost Vehicle Sustainment Contract was awarded to Northrop Grumman in September 2021 and the Exoatmospheric Kill Vehicle Sustainment Contract was
 awarded to Raytheon Missile Systems in June 2023. The Ground Based Interceptor Integration and Test acquisition is planned for award to The Boeing Company
 in FY 2025. These contracts are intended primarily to ensure fleet viability until the replacement Next Generation Interceptors are fielded. These Contractors perform
 Interceptor Fleet management consisting of service life extensions, maintaining the existing fleet, and executing repairs.



