FY 2024 Accomplishments: The research focused on providing sustained and distributed measurements of
ice-ocean-atmosphere conditions along the Arctic coast. The scientific focus was on the evolution of coastal sea
ice, especially the landfast ice that buffers the coastal zone and provides an important seasonal platform for the
local community. The goal was to seek an understanding of the drivers of break-out events in spring, including
the balance of thermodynamics (heat and light) compared with dynamics (winds, waves, currents). Specific
objectives.

(1) Developed instruments and approaches to facilitate the maintenance and operation of Arctic coastal
observing systems by local communities, relying on personnel, skills and resources that are locally available.
(2) Reduced latency in data return from ice-covered coastal zones, with the goal of achieving data exfiltration on
timescales useful for supporting accurate forecasts. (3) Combined ice-based and ocean-drifting measurements
with fixed moorings to provide distributed spatial and temporal measurements along the coast.
